<font color="#FF0000">SECOND TOUR, WHY NOT!</font><br>
<tt>Sat Aug  2 14:05:04 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Why a Second Tour<br>
For the Money, for the pay for the glory, for guts sweat and tears.<br>
To see places, death and destruction you didn't see before.<br>
To get a second set of &quot;ears&quot;<br>
To be greeted at San Francisco airport by a different set of protestors, spitting, shouting and cursing at you.<br><br>
A second tour?<br>
Everyone that was in our unit that went back regretted it.<br>
It was not the same they said, the camaraderie, the unity, trust, discipline it was all gone. Drugs and discipline was also a problem we had not encountered in the first tour. Gone also was the leadership and commitment to the war and the Vietnamese people.<br><br>
It was no longer small unit operations but company size or larger with a lot of dead time in between. Artillery, Naval gunfire and air strikes took over much of the combat response. It was not the same. <br><br>

